<span class="displaytext"><center><b><i>"our jim acosta talked with your senior strategist david axelrod about this. in 1995, william ayers held kind of a get-to-know you event at his place where he was introducing (candidate full) to the political culture there in chicago when he was running for the state senate for the first time. david axelrod said that at that meeting senator (candidate last) was not aware of ayers' radical background."</i> -- cnn's john roberts</b></center> <p><b>cnn's "american morning"<br/> october 6, 2008</b></p><p> <b>cnn's john roberts:</b> "i just want to try to get to the heart of it so that people at home can understand. our jim acosta talked with your senior strategist david axelrod about this. in 1995, william ayers held kind of a get-to-know you event at his place where he was introducing (candidate full) to the political culture there in chicago when he was running for the state senate for the first time. david axelrod said that at that meeting senator (candidate last) was not aware of ayers' radical background. is that true?" </p><p><b>(candidate last) senior strategist robert gibbs:</b> "look, if that's what david said, that is true. look, again, this is a relationship, excuse me, that (candidate full) has condemned the actions of bill ayers. this is somebody that the new york times said (candidate full)'s not close to, and, again, john, this is a way of distracting the american people from what's important." </p><p><i><b><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cuji-owk__s">watch</a> the new (candidate last) campaign defense</b></i> </p><p><b><u>fact check: axelrod has said ayers and (candidate last) are "certainly friendly," and the (candidate last) campaign has never before said (candidate last) didn't know ayers' radical and violent history -- but has referred to him as "respected advisor" to chicago mayor</u></b> </p><p><b>when <i>politico</i> first reported on (candidate last)'s 1995 meeting at william ayers' home reportedly launching his campaign, the (candidate last) campaign never said he didn't know ayers' radical history.</b> "in 1995, state senator alice palmer introduced her chosen successor, (candidate full), to a few of the district's influential liberals at the home of two well known figures on the local left: william ayers and bernardine dohrn. while ayers and dohrn may be thought of in hyde park as local activists, they're better known nationally as two of the most notorious -- and unrepentant -- figures from the violent fringe of the 1960s anti-war movement. ... i can remember being one of a small group of people who came to bill ayers' house to learn that alice palmer was stepping down from the senate and running for congress,' said dr. quentin young, a prominent chicago physician and advocate for single-payer health care, of the informal gathering at the home of a yers and his wife, dohrn. [palmer] identified [(candidate last)] as her successor.' (candidate last)'s campaign dismisses the notion that his relationship with ayers should be seen through the lens of the latter's violent past, or his present lack of regret for the bombings. ... he described ayers as a professor of education at the university of illinois-chicago and a former aide to mayor richard j. daley,' referring to printed reports that he had "advised" daley on school reform. dr. young and another guest, maria warren, described it similarly: as an introduction to hyde park liberals of the handpicked successor to palmer, a well-regarded figure on the left. when i first met (candidate full), he was giving a standard, innocuous little talk in the living room of those two legends-in-their-own-minds, bill ayers and bernardine dohrn,' warren wrote on her blog in 2005. they were launching him -- introducing him to the hyde park community as the best thing since sliced bread.'" (ben smith, "(candidate last) once visited 60s radicals," <a href="http://dyn.politico.com/printstory.cfm?uuid=3fc289d8-3048-5c12-009ad5180c22ff0b">the politico</a>, 1/22/08) </p><p><b>when senator (candidate full) made similar attack, (candidate last) campaign never made argument that he didn't know about (candidate last)'s radical and violent past.</b> ((candidate last) for america, "fact check on (candidate last) and ayers, <a href="http://factcheck.(candidate full).com/factcheck/2008/04/17/fact_check_on_(candidate last)_attacks.php">factcheck.(candidate full).com</a>, 4/17/08) </p><p><b>(candidate last) campaign argued that ayers was "respected advisor" to chicago mayor daley, and that "charges against ayers were dropped and he served no time."</b> ((candidate last) for america, "fact check on (candidate last) and ayers, <a href="http://factcheck.(candidate full).com/factcheck/2008/04/17/fact_check_on_(candidate last)_attacks.php">factcheck.(candidate full).com</a>, 4/17/08) </p><p><b>axelrod has previously said (candidate last) and ayers are "certainly friendly."</b> axelrod: "they're certainly friendly, they know each other, as anyone whose kids go to school together." (ben smith, "ax on ayers," <a href="http://www.politico.com/blogs/bensmith/0208/ax_on_ayers.html">www.politico.com</a>, 2/26/08) </p><p><b>two years after meeting ayers, (candidate last) published "rave review" of ayers' book in the chicago tribune, and jointly appeared on academic panels together.</b> "the two men were involved in efforts to reform the city's education system. they appeared together on academic panels, including one organized by michelle (candidate last) to discuss the juvenile justice system, an area of mutual concern. mr. ayers's book on the subject won a rave review in the chicago tribune by mr. (candidate last), who called it a searing and timely account.'" (jo becker and christopher drew, "pragmatic politics, forged on the south side," the new york times, 5/11/08)</p></span>



